# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: azure-sql-database
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] In computer science, **ACID** (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) is a set of properties of database transactions intended to guarantee data validity despite errors, power failures, and other mishaps.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] For example, a transfer of funds from one bank account to another, involving multiple changes such as debiting one account and crediting another, is a single transaction.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] In 1983, Andreas Reuter and Theo Härder coined the acronym *ACID*, building on earlier work by Jim Gray who named atomicity, consistency, and durability, but not isolation, when characterizing the transaction concept.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] These four properties are the major guarantees of the transaction paradigm, which has influenced many aspects of development in database systems.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] According to Gray and Reuter, the IBM Information Management System supported ACID transactions as early as 1973 (although the acronym was created later).
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] BASE stands for **b**asically **a**vailable, **s**oft state, and **e**ventually consistent: the acronym highlights that BASE is opposite of ACID, like their chemical equivalents, acid and base.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] A database either leans towards ACID or BASE, but it cannot be both (according to CAP theorem).
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] For example, SQL databases (like MySQL, PostgreSQL, AWS RedShift) are structured over the ACID model, while NoSQL databases (like DynamoDB or MongoDB) use the BASE architecture.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] However, some NoSQL databases might exhibit certain ACID traits.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Transactions are often composed of multiple statements.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Atomicity guarantees that each transaction is treated as a single "unit", which either succeeds completely or fails completely: if any of the statements constituting a transaction fails to complete, the entire transaction fails and the database is left unchanged.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] An atomic system must guarantee atomicity in each and every situation, including power failures, errors, and crashes.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] A guarantee of atomicity prevents updates to the database from occurring only partially, which can cause greater problems than rejecting the whole series outright.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] As a consequence, the transaction cannot be observed to be in progress by another database client.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] At one moment in time, it has not yet happened, and at the next, it has already occurred in whole (or nothing happened if the transaction was cancelled in progress).
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Consistency ensures that a transaction can only bring the database from one consistent state to another, preserving database invariants: any data written to the database must be valid according to all defined rules, including constraints, cascades, triggers, and any combination thereof.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] This prevents database corruption by an illegal transaction.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] An example of a database invariant is referential integrity, which guarantees the primary key–foreign key relationship.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Transactions are often executed concurrently (e.g., multiple transactions reading and writing to a table at the same time).
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Isolation ensures that concurrent execution of transactions leaves the database in the same state that would have been obtained if the transactions were executed sequentially.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Isolation is the main goal of concurrency control; depending on the isolation level used, the effects of an incomplete transaction might not be visible to other transactions.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Durability guarantees that once a transaction has been committed, it will remain committed even in the case of a system failure (e.g., power outage or crash).
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] This usually means that completed transactions (or their effects) are recorded in non-volatile memory.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] The following examples further illustrate the ACID properties.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] In these examples, the database table has two columns, A and B.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] An integrity constraint requires that the value in A and the value in B must sum to 100.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Atomicity is the guarantee that series of database operations in an atomic transaction will either all occur (a successful operation), or none will occur (an unsuccessful operation).
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] The series of operations cannot be separated with only some of them being executed, which makes the series of operations "indivisible".
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] In other words, atomicity means indivisibility and irreducibility.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Alternatively, we may say that a logical transaction may be composed of several physical transactions.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Unless and until all component physical transactions are executed, the logical transaction will not have occurred.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] An example of an atomic transaction is a monetary transfer from bank account A to account B.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] It consists of two operations, withdrawing the money from account A and depositing it to account B.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] We would not want to see the amount removed from account A before we are sure it has also been transferred into account B.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Performing these operations in an atomic transaction ensures that the database remains in a consistent state, that is, money is neither debited nor credited if either of those two operations fails.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Consistency is a very general term, which demands that the data must meet all validation rules.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] In the previous example, the validation is a requirement that *A* + *B* = 100.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] All validation rules must be checked to ensure consistency.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Assume that a transaction attempts to subtract 10 from *A* without altering *B*.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Because consistency is checked after each transaction, it is known that *A* + *B* = 100 before the transaction begins.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] If the transaction removes 10 from *A* successfully, atomicity will be achieved.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] However, a validation check will show that *A* + *B* = 90, which is inconsistent with the rules of the database.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] The entire transaction must be canceled and the affected rows rolled back to their pre-transaction state.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] If there had been other constraints, triggers, or cascades, every single change operation would have been checked in the same way as above before the transaction was committed.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Similar issues may arise with other constraints.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] We may have required the data types of both *A* and *B* to be integers.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] If we were then to enter, say, the value 13.5 for *A*, the transaction will be canceled, or the system may give rise to an alert in the form of a trigger (if/when the trigger has been written to this effect).
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Another example would be integrity constraints, which would not allow us to delete a row in one table whose primary key is referred to by at least one foreign key in other tables.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] To demonstrate isolation, we assume two transactions execute at the same time, each attempting to modify the same data.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] One of the two must wait until the other completes in order to maintain isolation.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] If these operations are performed in order, isolation is maintained, although T2 must wait.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Consider what happens if T1 fails halfway through.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] The database eliminates T1's effects, and T2 sees only valid data.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Again, consider what happens if T1 fails while modifying B in Step 4.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] By the time T1 fails, T2 has already modified A; it cannot be restored to the value it had before T1 without leaving an invalid database.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] This is known as a write-write contention, because two transactions attempted to write to the same data field.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] In a typical system, the problem would be resolved by reverting to the last known good state, canceling the failed transaction T1, and restarting the interrupted transaction T2 from the good state.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Consider a transaction that transfers 10 from A to B.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] First, it removes 10 from A, then it adds 10 to B.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] At this point, the user is told the transaction was a success.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] However, the changes are still queued in the disk buffer waiting to be committed to disk.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Power fails and the changes are lost, but the user assumes (understandably) that the changes persist.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Processing a transaction often requires a sequence of operations that is subject to failure for a number of reasons.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] For instance, the system may have no room left on its disk drives, or it may have used up its allocated CPU time.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] There are two popular families of techniques: write-ahead logging and shadow paging.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] In both cases, locks must be acquired on all information to be updated, and depending on the level of isolation, possibly on all data that may be read as well.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] In write ahead logging, durability is guaranteed by writing the prospective change to a persistent log before changing the database.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] That allows the database to return to a consistent state in the event of a crash.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] In shadowing, updates are applied to a partial copy of the database, and the new copy is activated when the transaction commits.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Many databases rely upon locking to provide ACID capabilities.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Locking means that the transaction marks the data that it accesses so that the DBMS knows not to allow other transactions to modify it until the first transaction succeeds or fails.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] The lock must always be acquired before processing data, including data that is read but not modified.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Non-trivial transactions typically require a large number of locks, resulting in substantial overhead as well as blocking other transactions.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] For example, if user A is running a transaction that has to read a row of data that user B wants to modify, user B must wait until user A's transaction completes.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Two-phase locking is often applied to guarantee full isolation.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] An alternative to locking is multiversion concurrency control, in which the database provides each reading transaction the prior, unmodified version of data that is being modified by another active transaction.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] This allows readers to operate without acquiring locks, i.e., writing transactions do not block reading transactions, and readers do not block writers.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Going back to the example, when user A's transaction requests data that user B is modifying, the database provides A with the version of that data that existed when user B started his transaction.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] User A gets a consistent view of the database even if other users are changing data.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] One implementation, namely snapshot isolation, relaxes the isolation property.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Guaranteeing ACID properties in a distributed transaction across a distributed database, where no single node is responsible for all data affecting a transaction, presents additional complications.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Network connections might fail, or one node might successfully complete its part of the transaction and then be required to roll back its changes because of a failure on another node.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] The two-phase commit protocol (not to be confused with two-phase locking) provides atomicity for distributed transactions to ensure that each participant in the transaction agrees on whether the transaction should be committed or not.
[src:azure-sql-database/acid] Briefly, in the first phase, one node (the coordinator) interrogates the other nodes (the participants), and only when all reply that they are prepared does the coordinator, in the second phase, formalize the transaction.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] A **cloud database** is a database that typically runs on a cloud computing platform, with access provided as a service.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] There are two common deployment models: users can run databases on the cloud independently, using a virtual machine image, or they can purchase access to a database service maintained by a cloud database provider.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] Cloud databases may use either a relational SQL or a NoSQL data model.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] Database services handle scalability and high availability, while making the underlying software stack transparent to users.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] Cloud platforms allow users to purchase virtual machine instances for a limited time, on which a database can be run.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] Users can upload their own machine image with a database installed or use ready-made machine images that include an optimized installation of a database.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] With a database as a service (DBaaS) model, users pay a cloud provider for database services and computing resources, which may reduce the operational overhead needed to develop and manage databases.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] Users are provided with tools to create and manage database instances, as well as to manage database users.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] Some cloud providers also offer tools for managing database structures and data.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] The design and development of typical systems often use data management and relational databases as key building blocks.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] Advanced queries expressed in SQL work well with the strict relationships imposed by relational databases.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] However, relational database technology was not originally designed for use over distributed systems.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] This limitation has been addressed through clustering enhancements, although some fundamental operations—such as data synchronization—still require complex and expensive protocols.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] Modern relational databases can exhibit poor performance on data-intensive systems.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] As a result, the NoSQL paradigm has been adopted within database management systems for cloud-based systems.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] NoSQL storage does not require fixed table schemas, and join operations are typically avoided.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] NoSQL databases have been shown to provide efficient horizontal scalability, high performance, and ease of integration into cloud applications.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] Additionally, data models that rely on simplified relay algorithms have been employed in data-intensive cloud mapping applications specific to virtual frameworks.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] It is also important to differentiate between cloud databases which are relational (SQL) and those that are non-relational (NoSQL).
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] SQL databases can run in the cloud either on virtual machines or as a managed service, depending on the vendor.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] While SQL databases are generally easy to scale vertically, horizontal scalability presents a greater challenge.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] making them well suited to cloud environments.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] However, many contemporary applications are built around a relational (SQL) data model, so adopting NoSQL databases often requires significant changes to application code.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] or similar variants), and key-value store data types.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] Multi-model databases combine relational and non-relational capabilities, providing a standard SQL interface to users and applications.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] Native multi-model databases support multiple data models with a single core, facilitating their use in applications built around SQL.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-as-a-service] The following table lists notable database vendors that offer cloud database services, classified by deployment model—machine image or database as a service—and by data model (SQL or NoSQL).
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] A **database transaction** symbolizes a unit of work, performed within a database management system (or similar system) against a database, that is treated in a coherent and reliable way independent of other transactions.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] A transaction generally represents any change in a database.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] To provide isolation between programs accessing a database concurrently.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] If this isolation is not provided, the programs' outcomes are possibly erroneous.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] In a database management system, a transaction is a single unit of logic or work, sometimes made up of multiple operations.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] Any logical calculation done in a consistent mode in a database is known as a transaction.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] One example is a transfer from one bank account to another: the complete transaction requires subtracting the amount to be transferred from one account and adding that same amount to the other.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] Database practitioners often refer to these properties of database transactions using the acronym ACID.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] Databases and other data stores which treat the integrity of data as paramount often include the ability to handle transactions to maintain the integrity of data.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] A single transaction consists of one or more independent units of work, each reading and/or writing information to a database or other data store.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] When this happens it is often important to ensure that all such processing leaves the database or data store in a consistent state.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] Examples from double-entry accounting systems often illustrate the concept of transactions.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] In double-entry accounting every debit requires the recording of an associated credit.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] A transactional system would make both entries pass or both entries would fail.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] By treating the recording of multiple entries as an atomic transactional unit of work the system maintains the integrity of the data recorded.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] In other words, nobody ends up with a situation in which a debit is recorded but no associated credit is recorded, or vice versa.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] A **transactional database** is a DBMS that provides the ACID properties for a bracketed set of database operations (begin-commit).
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] Transactions ensure that the database is always in a consistent state, even in the event of concurrent updates and failures.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] All the write operations within a transaction have an all-or-nothing effect, that is, either the transaction succeeds and all writes take effect, or otherwise, the database is brought to a state that does not include any of the writes of the transaction.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] Transactions also ensure that the effect of concurrent transactions satisfies certain guarantees, known as isolation level.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] The highest isolation level is serializability, which guarantees that the effect of concurrent transactions is equivalent to their serial (i.e. sequential) execution.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] Most modern relational database management systems support transactions.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] NoSQL databases prioritize scalability along with supporting transactions in order to guarantee data consistency in the event of concurrent updates and accesses.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] In a database system, a transaction might consist of one or more data-manipulation statements and queries, each reading and/or writing information in the database.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] Users of database systems consider consistency and integrity of data as highly important.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] Execute a set of data manipulations and/or queries.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] If no error occurs, then commit the transaction.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] If an error occurs, then roll back the transaction.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] A transaction commit operation persists all the results of data manipulations within the scope of the transaction to the database.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] A transaction rollback operation does not persist the partial results of data manipulations within the scope of the transaction to the database.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] In no case can a partial transaction be committed to the database since that would leave the database in an inconsistent state.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] Internally, multi-user databases store and process transactions, often by using a transaction ID or XID.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] There are multiple varying ways for transactions to be implemented other than the simple way documented above.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] Nested transactions, for example, are transactions which contain statements within them that start new transactions (i.e. sub-transactions).
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] *Multi-level transactions* are a variant of nested transactions where the sub-transactions take place at different levels of a layered system architecture (e.g., with one operation at the database-engine level, one operation at the operating-system level).
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] Another type of transaction is the compensating transaction.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] Transactions are available in most SQL database implementations, though with varying levels of robustness.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] For example, MySQL began supporting transactions from early version 3.23, but the InnoDB storage engine was not default before version 5.5.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] The earlier available storage engine, MyISAM does not support transactions.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] A transaction is typically started using the command `BEGIN` (although the SQL standard specifies `START TRANSACTION`).
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] When the system processes a `COMMIT` statement, the transaction ends with successful completion.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] A `ROLLBACK` statement can also end the transaction, undoing any work performed since `BEGIN`.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] If autocommit was disabled with the start of a transaction, autocommit will also be re-enabled with the end of the transaction.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] One can set the isolation level for individual transactional operations as well as globally.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] At the highest level (`READ COMMITTED`), the result of any operation performed after a transaction has started will remain invisible to other database users until the transaction has ended.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] At the lowest level (`READ UNCOMMITTED`), which may occasionally be used to ensure high concurrency, such changes will be immediately visible.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] Relational databases are traditionally composed of tables with fixed-size fields and records.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] Object databases comprise variable-sized blobs, possibly serializable or incorporating a mime-type.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] The fundamental similarities between Relational and Object databases are the start and the commit or rollback.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] After starting a transaction, database records or objects are locked, either read-only or read-write.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] Once the transaction is fully defined, changes are committed or rolled back atomically, such that at the end of the transaction there is no inconsistency.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] Database systems implement distributed transactions as transactions accessing data over multiple nodes.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] A distributed transaction enforces the ACID properties over multiple nodes, and might include systems such as databases, storage managers, file systems, messaging systems, and other data managers.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] In a distributed transaction there is typically an entity coordinating all the process to ensure that all parts of the transaction are applied to all relevant systems.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] Moreover, the integration of Storage as a Service (StaaS) within these environments is crucial, as it offers a virtually infinite pool of storage resources, accommodating a range of cloud-based data store classes with varying availability, scalability, and ACID properties.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] This integration is essential for achieving higher availability, lower response time, and cost efficiency in data-intensive applications deployed across cloud-based data stores.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] The Namesys Reiser4 filesystem for Linux supports transactions, and as of Microsoft Windows Vista, the Microsoft NTFS filesystem supports distributed transactions across networks.
[src:azure-sql-database/database-transaction] There is occurring research into more data coherent filesystems, such as the Warp Transactional Filesystem (WTF).
[src:azure-sql-database/microsoft-sql-server] The history of Microsoft SQL Server begins with the first Microsoft SQL Server product—SQL Server 1.0, a 16-bit server for the OS/2 operating system in 1989—and extends to the current day.
[src:azure-sql-database/microsoft-sql-server] Its name is entirely descriptive, it being *server* software that responds to queries in the *SQL* language.
[src:azure-sql-database/microsoft-sql-server] From SQL Server 2016 onward, the product is supported on x64 processors only and must have 1.4 GHz processor as a minimum, 2.0 GHz or faster is recommended.
[src:azure-sql-database/microsoft-sql-server] The current version is Microsoft SQL Server 2025, released November 18, 2025.
[src:azure-sql-database/microsoft-sql-server] Microsoft makes SQL Server available in multiple editions, with different feature sets and targeting different users.
